column1: courage is essential during all stages of life and every nuance of the now. you exhibit it every day in large and small ways.  to consciously tap into courage and break free from the cycle of rumination and hesitation that keeps me stuck in my mind
column2: i listen to the intelligence of my body

column1: â€¢ â€œto be courageous is to seat our feelings deeply in the body and in the world; to live up to and into the necessities of relationships that often already exist
column2: with things we find we already care deeply about with a person
column5: or with an unknown that begs us on and always has begged us on. to be courageous is to stay close to the way we are made.

column1: the french philosopher camus used to tell himself quietly to â€˜live to the point of tears
column2: â€™ not as a call for maudlin sentimentality

column4: i would escape for a few minutes to my bathroom

column6: slowly catch my breath to bring myself back to a state of normalcy. some days i'd weep quietly others i would have little moments of hyperventilation. little did i know
column7: god was giving me bodily symptoms that i needed his shalom
column8: his sabbath rest. for in rest we heal; we reenergize. what's beautiful about biblical narratives is that we are modeled by earlier tribes how to do this ""resting"". god rested on the 7th day saying everything in his masterpiece was ""good""
column9: therefore our self-care and personal rest needs to be quantified under that condition. it must ""be good for us"". the early hebrews celebrated while resting with familial moments at the table

column15: & work. addictions develop and we cope in destructive ways to numb our body's cry for this much needed rest. may this be a sweet reminder that god made you perfect
column16: just as you are. he made you godly ""good"". and your creator wants you to rest and remember his love for you--his child. #soulsolitudemoments #authorsofinstagram #anxiety #trustthejourney

column1: 5493;instagram;2019-03-02 06:24:35;FALSE;"this time last year i marched with some of my nearest and dearest in the 40th anniversary of mardi gras. this year i find myself in the us missing my friends and family
column2: but living a very lucky life to say the least.

column1: mardi gras for me represents a celebration of all things diverse and i know there are people that have fought long and hard for that privilege and will continue to do so. to those i am thankful and eternally grateful.
iâ€™m fortunate to be part of the rainbow community and i acknowledge there are other communities and groups that suffer under similar circumstances. the fight is not over.
i know i live in a bubble of support from friends and family that others are not so fortunate to have. to all of you i thank and love you and know you are loved.
i say to the bigots and ignorant people of this world. grow the fuck up!
be the change and accept people for who they are for the world will be a better place. i need not mention the naysayers who are now convicted of crimes beyond belief.
to those that feel alone and isolated
column2: know that it does get better. there are people that love you and will support you. you are not alone. find your family.

column1: 5596;instagram;2019-03-02 10:23:43;FALSE;"this week @nbcbrooklyn99 addressed the issue of #metoo. as a result of the episode i have had conversations with men around me about the common occurrence of sexual harassment and abuse. literally every woman i know has had some experience with it.
what's really standing out about these conversations
column3: is that many good men feel sick that they can't relate to or understand what it's like to be a woman and to have these experiences.

column1: you can't know. don't blame yourself for not knowing what something is like when you have not experienced it first hand. and to be honest
column2: i'm happy you don't know first hand. i'm happy for you.

column1: why is this my response? because i am a lover of people. i don't discriminate between gender
column2: race or sexual orientation. we all have privileges and we all have pain. i'm rooting for all people

column1: does this mean that i deny these issues?

column2: no!! the issues are real and the key is vulnerable #communication. as long as you keep attacking people for what they don't understand
column3: they will understand it even less and resist it even more.

column1: thank you @stephaniebeatriz for directing this amazing episode. beautiful writing. great job.";;en;#metoo.

column2: a group of 30 bangaloreans gathered at our courtyard to discuss the art vs artist issue
we have been pondering over how to look at the issue
column3: whether to dismiss art created by artists accused of misdeeds
column4: or view an artwork as having its own life

column1: in a most engaging discussion moderated by pavithra sankaran
column2: we managed to touch upon various aspects of the problem by creating a safe space for conversation. from the role of the individual vs collective opinion
column3: to the role of social media in todayâ€™s outrage culture
column4: to the sharing of experiences and thoughts on the matter
column5: it was a wholesome discussion that brought up and addressed some essential questions
column6: as well as threw light on the grey areas.

column2: it was not easy to come to one conclusion or solution given the vastness of the topic. here are a few thought-provoking questions that came up which weâ€™d like to leave you to think about: -what are the implications of separating an artwork from the artist? -in the #metoo era
column3: do artworks made my wrongdoers deserve a place in museums and galleries? -by appreciating or looking at a work made by a known miscreant
column4: are you enabling the perpetrator? -is boycotting and public shaming the only way to tackle this issue? or are there more humane solutions like reforms? -finally
column5: what is your take on the issue?

column1: you can share your thoughts in the comments section or email us atinfo@thecourtyardcommunity.in. we hope to have many more such open discussions in the near future.

column1: 5740;instagram;2019-03-02 13:54:29;FALSE;"it's been a long time coming but i'm happy to announce after months apart and a year and a half in transition
column2: keeva and i are both together
column3: home and happy with our little spot of the woods in connecticut.

column1: last year this time i was very ill
column3: and trying to find my way back to a new normal without knowing what that could mean.

column1: now i'm a substitute teacher at an arts magnet elementary school. i hear tiny voices squeal 'ms. beeeeeeeeeeeee!' when i walk around the halls. i get hugs (and tears)
column2: stories and questions all day long. i get to impart mindfulness and self-care techniques with my tiny friends and watch them understand new perspectives.

column1: my fridge is now covered in drawings
column2: a fridge in a beautiful house i get to share with my wonderful partner

column1: living with multiple chronic illnesses means i'm never not 'sick'. working in an elementary school means i'm never far from a stomach bug or two - the running count is two within 7 weeks - but living with someone who loves me despite the things i can't help
column2: who listens to all my complaints and worries
column3: is there for all my midnight diabetes low blood sugars and ptsd triggers
column4: has made all the difference. for the first time in a very
column5: very long time i feel mostly whole
column6: happy and optimistic about the future. the view is pretty damned good from this little patch of the world.

column2: stories and questions all day long. i get to impart mindfulness and self-care techniques with my tiny friends and watch them understand new perspectives.

column1: my fridge is now covered in drawings
column2: a fridge in a beautiful house i get to share with my wonderful partner

column1: living with multiple chronic illnesses means i am never not 'sick'. working in an elementary school means i am never far from a stomach bug or two - the running count is two within 7 weeks - but living with someone who loves me despite the things i can not help
column2: who listens to all my complaints and worries
column3: is there for all my midnight diabetes low blood sugars and ptsd triggers
column4: has made all the difference. for the first time in a very
column5: very long time i feel mostly whole
column6: happy and optimistic about the future. the view is pretty damned good from this little patch of the world.
